%%TITLE
Staging and treatment of oropharyngeal cancer in the human papillomavirus era.
%%ABSTRACT
Oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (SCC) is staged using the TNM system. Human papillomavirus (HPV)-positive tumors have improved prognosis, despite presenting at advanced stage. Optimal treatment and stratification of HPV-positive patients are not clearly defined.We retrospectively analyzed 266 patients with oropharyngeal SCC for mortality and feeding tube dependency related to TNM stage, HPV status, and treatment.TNM staging was prognostic in HPV-negative patients (stage III/IV hazard ratio [HR], 2.00; p = .05; N(+) HR, 2.19; p = .02). Only T classification was prognostic in HPV-positive tumors (T3/T4 HR 3.31; p = .006). HPV-positive tumors showed improved survival regardless of treatment. Patients receiving chemotherapy had a significantly increased risk of feeding tube dependency (odds ratio [OR], 1.72; p = .03).These data suggest that the current TNM system has little prognostic value in HPV-positive oropharyngeal SCC. Patients with HPV-positive tumors show improved survival independent of treatment. The addition of chemotherapy increases the risk of feeding tube dependency and could potentially be avoided in T1/T2 HPV-positive tumors without compromising survival.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
We retrospectively identified 442 patients treated con- secutively for oropharyngeal SCC at University Hospital Southampton NHS Trust (UHS, 2000–2010), Poole Hos- pitals NHS Trust (PFT, 2000–2006), and Barts and the London NHS Trust (BLT, 2000–2006). We performed a retrospective case note analysis recording demographic details, tumor subsite, and risk factors. Smoking was cate- gorized as less or greater than a 10 pack-year history, in accordance with recent studies demonstrating this level as predictive in both HPV-negative and HPV-positive oro- pharyngeal SCC.8,12 All tumors were restaged according to the most recent edition of the AJCC TNM staging for Head and Neck cancer.1 The final T classification and N classification were recorded and used to define the overall disease stage (I–IV). These variables were then simplified by recoding overall the disease stage and T classification into early and late (ie, stage: I/II vs III/IV, and T classifi- cation: T1/T2 vs T3/T4) and N classification into the presence or absence of nodal metastases. Nodal status was also summarized to take into account the “intermediate risk” group of HPV-positive patients, as suggested by Ang et al8 (ie, N0–N2a vs N2b and above). Patients were excluded if they had incomplete TNM stag-
ing, incomplete survival data, follow-up of <6 months, or
had received either palliative or no treatment. A total of
395 patients remained after these exclusions and, of these patients, archival pathology material was available for
269. The demographics of both patients groups (ie, those with and without pathology material available) are shown in Table 1. There was no difference in disease-specific survival (DSS) between these groups (DSS p 5 0.76; Supplementary data, online only). Ethical approval was obtained (UKCRN 8130; ISRCTN 71276356; REC refer- ences 09/H0501/90 and 07/Q0405/1).
Treatment
Treatment received was recorded as surgery alone, sur- gery with adjuvant therapy, RT alone, and CRT (Supple- mentary data, online only). For surgically treated patients, resection was recorded as either transoral or open. Patients receiving postoperative RT received 60 to 64 Gy in 30 to 32 fractions, whereas patients undergoing radical RT received 64 to 66 Gy in 32 to 33 fractions. No patients received altered fractionation or intensity- modulated RT. Concurrent chemotherapy consisted of 2 to 6 doses of either cisplatin or carboplatin, whereas neo- adjuvant chemotherapy was 1 to 2 doses of either cispla- tin or carboplatin in conjunction with 5-flurouracil. The requirement for nasogastric tube or PEG feeding during and after treatment was recorded, as was whether or not the feeding tube was removed, and after how long a period of time. For the purpose of further analysis, in this article, we define feeding tube dependency as having a feeding tube at the end of treatment. In addition, we also
calculated rates of long-term feeding tube dependency at 3 and 6 months.
Assessment of human papillomavirus status
Tumor histology was reviewed by a consultant histopathol- ogist (G.J.T.) blinded to treatment and outcome, according to 1998 United Kingdom Royal College of Pathologist Guide- lines, and a suitable paraffin block was selected. Tissue microarrays were constructed using triplicate, randomly selected, paraffin-embedded 1-mm tumor cores (Aphelys Minicore 2, Mitogen, UK). Sections from these TMAs were stained for p16 using immunohistochemistry (CINtec; Roche, Burgess Hill, West Sussex, UK) with an automated stainer in the histopathology department at UHS (Ventana XT; Ven- tana, Tuscon, AZ, USA) and tumors scored as either nega-
tive or positive (strong positivity in >70% of tumor cells).13 HPV in situ hybridization (ISH) was performed using
Genpoint HPV DNA Probe Cocktail (Dako, Ely, Cam- bridgeshire, UK), which recognizes the 13 most prevalent high-risk HPV genotypes, including HPV-16 and HPV-18. Cases were scored as negative or positive. Tumors positive both for p16 immunochemistry and HPV ISH were classi- fied as HPV-positive.14
Statistics
The main outcome measures were overall survival (OS) and disease specific survival (DSS). OS was defined as the length of time between the date of diagnosis and the date of death from any cause. Patients who were still alive at the time of the last follow-up were censored at this time point. DSS was defined as the length of time between the date of diagnosis and the date of death from oropharyngeal SCC. Patients who were still alive at the last follow-up, or who died from another cause, were censored at the date of last follow-up or the date of death, respectively. For all analy- ses, only DSS is presented in this article, whereas OS can be found in the supplementary information, online only.
The relationships between categorical variables were assessed by cross-tabulation and either Fisher exact test or chi-square test, as appropriate. Relationships between con- tinuous variables were assessed using the independent sam- ples t test for normally distributed data, and the Mann– Whitney U test for non-normally distributed data. Survival analysis was performed using Kaplan–Meier analysis with log-rank tests, and both univariate and multivariate Cox pro- portional hazards regression. Odds ratios (ORs) were calcu- lated using logistic regression. All statistical tests were 2- sided and a p value of .05 was considered significant. All statistical analysis was performed using SPSS for Windows version 19.0 (IBM, Portsmouth, Hampshire, UK).
